From 5baabfea13a15f78dadead092bf167e19c87ecb4 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Ashish Kumar Singh <ashishkmr472@gmail.com>
Date: Tue, 19 May 2026 21:32:07 -0400
Subject: [PATCH 07/10] a/t,tests: Make controller Kalman fusion thread-safe
 via seqlock snapshot
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

The Kalman fusion's get_prediction ran on SteamVR's ~1 kHz render thread
with no synchronization while process_imu_data (~210 Hz) and process_pose
(~60 Hz) mutated the 22-dim filter state from other threads. Torn reads
of the multi-word Eigen state produced catastrophic prediction spikes
(11 m / 171 m/s in recorded data), giving controllers a springy,
intermittently drifting feel.

Redesign uses a single-writer seqlock snapshot:

- Writers (already mutually exclusive via the WMR driver's data_lock,
  plus an internal std::mutex for generality) publish a trivially-copyable
  POD FilterSnapshot via a textbook seqlock — odd counter / body copy /
  even counter, release fences either side of the body.

- get_prediction reads the snapshot wait-free through the seqlock retry
  loop, then extrapolates with constant-acceleration kinematics + damping
  on the ~200 B POD. The previous 2 KB Eigen state copy and Eigen predict
  per-call are gone from the hot path.

- The per-IMU-sample std::queue<xrt_imu_sample> ff_samples allocation +
  copy is also eliminated; integration happens immediately under the
  filter lock with no deferred queue.

The published snapshot is alignas(64) to keep the seqlock counter and
state body off the writer's cache lines.

Tests: 20 cases / 584 assertions, all green. The new
"concurrent readers never observe a torn filter state" case spawns 4
reader threads against live IMU + optical writer threads for 400 ms
and verifies every read is finite and bounded — the exact regression
that would have caught the original race.

Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.7 (1M context) <noreply@anthropic.com>
